    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2199727780" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2199727780" />
    <a title="Adrian Lawrence" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69419225-adrian-lawrence"><img alt="Adrian Lawrence" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2199727780?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adrian Lawrence" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adrian Lawrence" href="/user/show/69419225-adrian-lawrence">Adrian Lawrence</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2199727780" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer391805170170208888">Non-thrilling romance￼<br/><br/>I thought the first book was disappointing so it was no surprise it&apos;s sequel revealed itself to be the same overall. The general plot is good with moments of suspense that are chilling. However, the characterisation of the main protagonists is poor. Firstly, there&apos;s the hunky former police officer hero, whose &quot;muscles aren&apos;t just for show&quot; that punches his open palm as a display of frustration. How many times do you have to read in both books &quot;tugged at his heart&quot; when he&apos;s</span>
  <span id="freeText391805170170208888" style="display:none">Non-thrilling romance￼<br /><br />I thought the first book was disappointing so it was no surprise it's sequel revealed itself to be the same overall. The general plot is good with moments of suspense that are chilling. However, the characterisation of the main protagonists is poor. Firstly, there's the hunky former police officer hero, whose "muscles aren't just for show" that punches his open palm as a display of frustration. How many times do you have to read in both books "tugged at his heart" when he's being portrayed as Mr. Ideal. Cringeworthy would be a good description of him and the sex scenes.Then there's the too-stupid-to-live attorney heroine who doesn't do much legal work at all in the book. Instead she appears to act as a private detective with the skill and common sence of any of the Scooby Doo cast; even down to the obligatory confession at the end. Her character is often inconsistent. Nevertheles, for the want of reasonable read, I'll put up with this. But what I found intolerable was the abundance of pages devoted to the heroine's family that had the book flatlining. The children's dialogue. The nanny that needed dialysis every Friday. The old grandad. It was crippling.There's at least eight relatives and they could all be dropped without affecting the plot; they don't add anything.<br />In summary the general plot is good enough for a generous four stars, although with holes both in transparency and implausible characters. The extended Mills and Boon romance theme is in conflict with the suspense throughout. Finally, too many needless characters.</span>
  <a data-text-id="391805170170208888" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


